<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-778-040  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 778 040.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 19 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Tokyo: computer fraud disclosed.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Takahashi, Ken.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     JapanComputer crimesFraudComputer Retailing.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>TOKYO: COMPUTER FRAUD DISCLOSED TOKYO, JAPAN, 1990 JUN 14 (NB) -- The TokyoMetropolitan Police Agency has arrested a person on a charge of defrauding agreat sum of money from a real estate agent who has no knowledge ofcomputers.andM;According to the police investigation, the suspect, named Toshiaki Kawashima,was a president of the computer store Urban located in the Chuo district ofTokyo, and had been jointly managing another computer-related firm with therealtor.andP;  Over the course of a few years, Kawashima came to disguise computerdeals to cheat his partner out of money, knowing that he did not have anyknowledge about computers, police say.andM;In November 1988, the alleged swindler made up a deal story to the realtorthat his acquaintance received an order from Japan's Defence Agency topurchase 25 computers, authorities say.andP;  Kawashima is said to have then askedhis partner for the money, saying they could earn few million yen per unit.andO;Kawashima showed elaborately made-up papers, such as an order form and abrokerage contract, to cheat about 220 million yen ($1.44 million) out of therealtor with the phony deal, say police.andM;The suspect is also believed to have swindled from the real estate agentabout another 570 million yen ($3.7 million) between April 1988 and January1989, by creating similar made-up stories.andM;(Ken Takahashi/19900614)</TEXT></DOC>